n to the Iranian Embassy at The Hague for the attention of the Shah, who is on a European trip.\n\nDaud Beg Jaf, a member of the Iraqi parliament before the 14 July 1958 revolution, is an ardent Kurdish separatist who has long sought American assistance for the creation of an independent Kurdistan. In pre-revolution times, he sharply exaggerated the strength of the tribal support which he could muster to his cause. The Jafs, a chronically unruly tribe of some 24 branches, frequently feud with each other. At least a few of these, however, have been hostile to the Qasim government; thus Daud Beg could probably call on the backing of at least 1,000 militant tribesmen.\n\nThe Iranian Government, while probably recognizing the exaggerated nature of Daud Beg's proposals, is nevertheless likely to give his tribesmen some clandestine support to encourage raids on Iraqi villages and security posts. Such support will probably be limited to small quantities of weapons and a promise of safe haven; it might also include a clandestine radio transmitter which Daud Beg requested.\n\nThe Shah can be expected to order that this support be furnished with great caution, so as to avoid Iran's identification with subversive activities in Iraq. The Shah is unlikely to pass up this new opportunity completely, however, since he has recently been informed that the clandestine \"free Iranian\" radio which has been advocating his overthrow is located in Iraqi territory", "token_count": 245, "token_end_0based": 304, "token_start_0based": 60, "token_text": "a message of 16 may from tehran to the iranian embassy at the hague for the attention of the shah who is on a european trip daud beg jaf a member of the iraqi parliament before the 14 july 1958 revolution is an ardent kurdish separatist who has long sought american assistance for the creation of an independent kurdistan in pre-revolution times he sharply exaggerated the strength of the tribal support which he could muster to his cause the jafs a chronically unruly tribe of some 24 branches frequently feud with each other at least a few of these however have been hostile to the qasim government thus daud beg could probably call on the backing of at least 1 000 militant tribesmen the iranian government while probably recognizing the exaggerated nature of daud beg's proposals is nevertheless likely to give his tribesmen some clandestine support to encourage raids on iraqi villages and security posts such support will probably be limited to small quantities of weapons and a promise of safe haven it might also include a clandestine radio transmitter which daud beg requested the shah can be expected to order that this support be furnished with great caution so as to avoid iran's identification with subversive activities in iraq the shah is unlikely to pass up this new opportunity completely however since he has recently been informed that the clandestine free iranian radio which has been advocating his overthrow is located in iraqi territory", "unred_source_page": 13}
